description: One of the most interesting hybrid swarms I have ever seen.  Acres of extremely variable plants.  A. nevadensis, mewukka, viscida, patula all present at this location.  I've been trying to get Mike Vasey and Tom Parker to check out this spot for years!  Not sure if any of the nevadensis is "pure" nevadensis.  All of it seems to be integrated with other genes.  Fairly low elevation for nevadensis for this region.  A lot of other interesting plants also present at this location (Calochortus coeruleous, Calochortus nudus/minimus and hybrids between this one and coeruleous, Erythronium purpurescens - very low elevation for this one). @morganstickrod @dgreenberger

description: Shrimp remain a world unknown to me.
I can't find pics or descriptions that quite match what I'm seeing here. Maybe Pseudoceros canadensis, maybe something in Eurylepta. About 20 mm long, observed in the intertidal. Pics taken in situ.

The only reasons I thought this was something other than E. prolifera was the unusally red column and the complete flat profile.  I foolishly neglected to take a pic of a flattened one.  Apparently another good field mark are the fat, white radii on the edge of disk that don't reach the center.
The antennae aren't super long like they're supposed to be in M. californiana, so maybe one of the others.  Not enough detail to tell with the key, I think.
The leaves don't look that hairy, so I'm going with F. californica. Not sure if Frangula or Rhamnus is the right genus to use, so I'll follow CalFlora.
